---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Symposion of the Green Fairy" description="Seven witnesses to absinthe gather‚Äîthose who lived with it, loved it, abused it, ritualized it, and made art or magic through it">
  <div class="absinthe-theme">
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-pattern"></div>
      <div class="container hero-content">
        <h1>Symposion of the Green Fairy</h1>
        <p class="hero-subtitle">Symposium on Absinthe</p>
        <p class="hero-format">6 voices + 1 heretic √ó 7 minutes ‚Ä¢ ~1 hour</p>
        <div class="hero-ornament">üçÉ ‚ú¶ üçÉ</div>
        
        <!-- Watch Presentation CTA -->
        <div class="hero-cta">
          <a href={`${base}/absinthe/present`} class="cta-button primary" target="_blank">
            <span class="cta-icon">‚ñ∂</span>
            Watch Presentation
            <span class="cta-badge">with AI voices</span>
          </a>
          <a href={`${base}/absinthe/001-opening`} class="cta-button secondary">
            Read Transcripts ‚Üí
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="overview container">
      <p class="lead">
        A fin-de-si√®cle Parisian caf√©, the hour suspended between twilight and midnight. 
        Green-tinted light filters through absinthe glasses arranged on marble tables. 
        Seven figures gather‚Äîartists, magicians, scientists, poets‚Äîeach bearing witness 
        to the Green Fairy from their own lived experience. Not theorists, but practitioners.
      </p>
      
      <blockquote class="question-block">
        <p class="question-english">What is absinthe?</p>
        <p class="question-sub">A substance, a symbol, a scapegoat, or a technology of transformation?</p>
      </blockquote>
    </section>

    <section class="speakers container">
      <h2>The Six Witnesses</h2>
      <p class="speakers-subtitle">Each speaks for 7 minutes on their encounter with the Green Fairy</p>
      
      <div class="speakers-grid">
        <article class="speaker-card">
          <div class="speaker-icon">üé®</div>
          <h3>Vincent van Gogh</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Martyr</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1853‚Äì1890</p>
          <p>Heavy drinker of absinthe and wine. Absinthe as perceptual intensifier‚Äîcolor, vibration, halos. The danger of retroactively blaming the substance instead of conditions.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> Perception, suffering, and the retroactive scapegoat</p>
        </article>

        <article class="speaker-card">
          <div class="speaker-icon">üîÆ</div>
          <h3>Aleister Crowley</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Magus</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1875‚Äì1947</p>
          <p>Deliberate, ritualized absinthe use. Absinthe as a technology of will, not escapism. Intoxication as threshold crossing‚Äîdiscipline vs dissipation.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> Intoxication as ritual technology</p>
        </article>

        <article class="speaker-card">
          <div class="speaker-icon">üí¨</div>
          <h3>Oscar Wilde</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Wit</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1854‚Äì1900</p>
          <p>Enthusiastic but ironic drinker. Absinthe as performance and social theater. Famous quips vs lived decline‚Äîthe aestheticization of intoxication.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> Absinthe as social artifice</p>
        </article>

        <article class="speaker-card">
          <div class="speaker-icon">üç∏</div>
          <h3>Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Chronicler</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1864‚Äì1901</p>
          <p>Invented absinthe cocktails; near-constant use. Caf√© culture embodied. Absinthe as social lubricant, not mysticism‚Äîthe artist as ethnographer of nightlife.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> The caf√© as laboratory</p>
        </article>

        <article class="speaker-card">
          <div class="speaker-icon">üî¨</div>
          <h3>Louis Pasteur</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Scientist</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1822‚Äì1895</p>
          <p>What was actually in the glass? Chemical analysis, fermentation, the thujone question. Data against myth‚Äîscience against hysteria.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> What was actually in the glass</p>
        </article>

        <article class="speaker-card">
          <div class="speaker-icon">‚öñÔ∏è</div>
          <h3>Michel Foucault</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Philosopher</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1926‚Äì1984</p>
          <p>Why the state feared the Fairy. Prohibition as biopower, the construction of deviance, absinthe as threat to social order.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> Why the state feared the Fairy</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="heretic-section">
        <p class="heretic-label">The Heretic</p>
        <article class="speaker-card heretic">
          <div class="speaker-icon">üíî</div>
          <h3>Paul Verlaine</h3>
          <p class="speaker-title">The Ruined Lyricist</p>
          <p class="speaker-dates">1844‚Äì1896</p>
          <p>Severe absinthe dependency: violence, madness, prison, collapse. The case prohibitionists loved. When the Green Fairy does devour‚Äîno redemption, only testimony.</p>
          <p class="speaker-contribution"><strong>Brings:</strong> The case for prohibition‚Äîdelivered from inside the wreckage</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="themes container">
      <h2>Themes Explored</h2>
      <ol class="themes-list">
        <li><strong>Perception & Altered States</strong> ‚Äî How does absinthe alter perception? What is the relationship between substance and experience?</li>
        <li><strong>Ritual & Intention</strong> ‚Äî Can intoxication be a technology of transformation? What distinguishes ritual from dissipation?</li>
        <li><strong>Performance & Social Theater</strong> ‚Äî How does absinthe function as social artifice? What masks does it enable?</li>
        <li><strong>Everyday Practice</strong> ‚Äî The caf√© as laboratory. Absinthe as social lubricant, not mysticism.</li>
        <li><strong>Science & Substance</strong> ‚Äî What was actually in the glass? Data against myth, analysis against hysteria.</li>
        <li><strong>Power & Prohibition</strong> ‚Äî Why did the state fear the Green Fairy? Prohibition as biopower and social control.</li>
        <li><strong>Ruin & Redemption</strong> ‚Äî When the Green Fairy devours. The case from inside the wreckage‚Äîno redemption, only testimony.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="sessions container">
      <h2>Sessions</h2>
      
      <!-- Presentation Mode Banner -->
      <a href={`${base}/absinthe/present`} class="presentation-banner" target="_blank">
        <div class="presentation-icon">üé≠</div>
        <div class="presentation-info">
          <h3>Interactive Presentation Mode</h3>
          <p>Watch the symposium with AI-generated voices, animated busts, and real-time subtitles. Submit questions for the Q&A session!</p>
        </div>
        <span class="presentation-cta">Launch ‚Üó</span>
      </a>
      
      <div class="sessions-list">
        <a href={`${base}/absinthe/001-opening`} class="session-card">
          <span class="session-number">001</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Opening: The Gathering</h3>
            <p>In which the seven are convened in the caf√© and the question is posed.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status available">Available</span>
        </a>
        
        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">002</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Van Gogh: Perception and the Retroactive Scapegoat</h3>
            <p>The martyr speaks of absinthe as perceptual intensifier and challenges the narrative that blames the substance.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>

        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">003</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Crowley: Intoxication as Ritual Technology</h3>
            <p>The magus presents absinthe as a deliberate tool of transformation, not escapism.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>

        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">004</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Wilde: Absinthe as Social Artifice</h3>
            <p>The wit performs absinthe as theater‚Äîcharm masking decay.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>

        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">005</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Toulouse-Lautrec: The Caf√© as Laboratory</h3>
            <p>The chronicler documents everyday absinthe‚Äînot mysticism, but social ritual.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>

        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">006</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Pasteur: What Was Actually in the Glass</h3>
            <p>The scientist brings data to the table‚Äîwhat was actually in the glass?</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>

        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">007</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Foucault: Why the State Feared the Fairy</h3>
            <p>The philosopher analyzes prohibition as biopower‚Äîwhy did the state fear the Green Fairy?</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>

        <div class="session-card planned">
          <span class="session-number">008</span>
          <div class="session-info">
            <h3>Verlaine: The Case from the Wreckage</h3>
            <p>The heretic speaks last, from inside the ruin‚Äîno redemption, only testimony.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="session-status">Planned</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="closing container">
      <div class="verse-block">
        <p class="verse-english">"After the first glass, you see things as you wish they were.</p>
        <p class="verse-english">After the second, you see things as they are not.</p>
        <p class="verse-english">Finally, you see things as they really are, and that is the most horrible thing in the world."</p>
        <p class="verse-attribution">‚Äî Oscar Wilde (attributed)</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
